00:43:29,480 --> 00:43:31,320
I can sense the weight of that word.

733
00:43:31,660 --> 00:43:33,520
What is the historical payload attached to it?

734
00:43:33,840 --> 00:43:38,820
To understand the weight of jawar, we have to step back into the golden age of Islamic philosophy.

735
00:43:39,900 --> 00:43:45,620
During the 9th and 10th centuries, scholars like al-Farabi and later Ibn Sina Avicenna in the West

736
00:43:45,620 --> 00:43:52,120
were engaged in a monumental project to translate, refine, and expand upon the metaphysical works of Aristotle.

737
00:43:52,240 --> 00:43:52,600
Right.

738
00:43:52,600 --> 00:43:58,840
Aristotle's foundational theory of existence proposed that the universe is divided into two fundamental categories.

739
00:43:59,060 --> 00:44:03,920
The first is substance, the underlying, essential, unchanging reality of a thing.

740
00:44:04,240 --> 00:44:10,740
The second is accident, the temporary, contingent, non-essential properties that adhere to the substance.

741
00:44:10,740 --> 00:44:12,880
So a human being is a substance.

742
00:44:12,880 --> 00:44:16,840
Being sunburned or being tired or being young, those are just accidents.

743
00:44:17,180 --> 00:44:20,160
They happen to the substance, but they don't define its fundamental nature.

744
00:44:20,520 --> 00:44:20,880
Precisely.

745
00:44:21,120 --> 00:44:24,520
And when the Islamic philosophers synthesized this metaphysical framework,

746
00:44:24,520 --> 00:44:30,580
the precise technical term they selected for Aristotle's substance, the immutable core, was jawar.

747
00:44:30,880 --> 00:44:35,420
And the term they used for the accident, the temporary peripheral property, was karad.

748
00:44:35,600 --> 00:44:39,720
Substance and accident, jawar and karad, inner orbit and outer orbit.

749
00:44:40,040 --> 00:44:44,860
They dedicated their lives to constructing staggeringly complex philosophical treatises,

750
00:44:45,380 --> 00:44:49,560
exploring the boundaries between the essential jawar and the contingent karin.

751
00:44:49,560 --> 00:44:53,160
It was the bleeding edge of intellectual inquiry for centuries.

752
